<subSubSection id="C37E6518FFBB0D47FEB5FA22FD21895A" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BDB3693FFBB0D47FEB5FA22FD21895A" blockId="4.[184,773,420,1966]" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis id="B910EA81FFBB0D47FEB5FA22FEF68BB7" bold="true" box="[184,309,1492,1516]" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
In 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF54B62FFBB0D47FF6AFA23FE378BB6" author="Stark, B. P." box="[359,500,1493,1517]" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" pagination="61 - 148" refId="ref3752" refString="Stark, B. P. 2004. Perlidae (The Stones). Pages 61 - 148. In Stark, B. P. &amp; B. J. Armitage, editors. Stoneflies (Plecoptera) of Eastern North America. Volume II. Chloroperlidae, Perlidae, and Perlodidae (Perlodinae). Ohio Biological Survey Bulletin New Series Volume 14. Columbus. 192 pp." type="book chapter" year="2004">Stark (2004)</bibRefCitation>
male specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D10FFBB0D47FCE3FA23FECA8854" authorityName="Kondratieff &amp; Zuellig &amp; Kirchner &amp; Lenat" authorityYear="2006" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bjostadi">
<emphasis id="B910EA81FFBB0D47FCE3FA23FECA8854" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">P. bjostadi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will key to couplet 16 which ends in 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D10FFBB0D47FCE3FA0EFDC48869" authority="DeWalt and Stark" authorityName="DeWalt and Stark" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="golconda">
<emphasis id="B910EA81FFBB0D47FCE3FA0EFED78869" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">P. golconda</emphasis>
DeWalt and Stark
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D10FFBB0D47FC5BF9ECFCC38869" authority="Stark" authorityName="Stark" authorityYear="1989" box="[598,768,1562,1586]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lagoi">
<emphasis id="B910EA81FFBB0D47FC5BF9ECFD738869" box="[598,688,1562,1586]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">P. lagoi</emphasis>
Stark
</taxonomicName>
, however, the unique paraprocts of 
<emphasis id="B910EA81FFBB0D47FC31F9CBFD6D880F" box="[572,686,1596,1620]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">
<taxonomicName id="4C644D10FFBB0D47FC31F9CBFD69880F" authorityName="Kondratieff &amp; Zuellig &amp; Kirchner &amp; Lenat" authorityYear="2006" box="[572,682,1596,1620]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bjostadi">P. bjostadi</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
lacking a prominent subapical or anteapical tooth will easily distinguish it from these two species. The adeagus of 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D10FFBB0D47FEB5F953FEEE88E7" authorityName="Kondratieff &amp; Zuellig &amp; Kirchner &amp; Lenat" authorityYear="2006" box="[184,301,1700,1724]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bjostadi">
<emphasis id="B910EA81FFBB0D47FEB5F953FEEE88E7" box="[184,301,1700,1724]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">P. bjostadi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D10FFBB0D47FFD0F953FD9F88E7" box="[477,604,1700,1724]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="golconda">
<emphasis id="B910EA81FFBB0D47FFD0F953FD9F88E7" box="[477,604,1700,1724]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">P. golconda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, both species having a small nipple at the base of the sac (
<figureCitation id="135F2A16FFBB0D47FCA7F930FD3B8884" box="[682,760,1734,1759]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[184,234,1820,1844]" captionTargetBox="[271,1327,373,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-46@3.[242,1344,341,1777]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 9-15. Perlesta bjostadi. 9, Adult head and pronotum. 10, Male terminalia, dorsal. 11, Paraproct, lateral. 12, Paraproct tip, lateral. 13, Paraproct caudal, 14, Penis, 15, Subgenital plate, ventral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4754591" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4754591/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). Unfortunately, no eggs were available for study.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37E6518FFBB0D47FEB5F8FAFC018A72" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BDB3693FFBB0D47FEB5F8FAFC018A72" blockId="4.[184,773,420,1966]" lastBlockId="4.[808,1404,315,1169]" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis id="B910EA81FFBB0D47FEB5F8FAFEEB897F" bold="true" box="[184,296,1804,1828]" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">Remarks.</emphasis>
This downstream portion of the Lower Little River is also in Cape Fear subbasin 14 (http://www.esb.enr.state.nc.us/bar.html) and located in the Sandhills ecoregion (Griffith et al. 2004, Kondratieff et al. 2005). There is no water chemistry data collected at the Hwy 410 site, but there is a NC monitoring station at Hwy 210, about 
<quantity id="4C9C9B76FFBB0D47FB24FEA8FAB88F2D" box="[1321,1403,350,374]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" unit="km" value="24.0">24 km</quantity>
upstream. Relative to the Morrison Bridge site (discussed under 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D10FFBB0D47FDF8FE52FB4D8FE0" authorityName="Kondratieff &amp; Zuellig &amp; Kirchner &amp; Lenat" authorityYear="2006" box="[1013,1166,419,443]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leathermani">
<emphasis id="B910EA81FFBB0D47FDF8FE52FB4D8FE0" box="[1013,1166,419,443]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">P. leathermani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
section), this part of the river is much larger (mean width 
<quantity id="4C9C9B76FFBB0D47FAD1FE33FAFB8F85" box="[1244,1336,453,478]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" unit="m" value="27.5" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="25.0">25-30 m</quantity>
) with slightly higher pH (median = 6.3), higher specific conductance (median = 47 umhos/cm) and higher nutrient values (NCDENR 2004). Both the higher nutrients and reduced shading produce prolific periphyton growths during the summer, although this site has consistently been rated as Excellent by NCDENR based on the macroinvertebrate community. Like the Morrison Bridge site, the Hwy 410 site has a sand and gravel substrate with humiccolored water. While collecting 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D10FFBB0D47FA81FCD6FB3A8D6C" authorityName="Kondratieff &amp; Zuellig &amp; Kirchner &amp; Lenat" authorityYear="2006" box="[1164,1273,799,823]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bjostadi">
<emphasis id="B910EA81FFBB0D47FA81FCD6FB3A8D6C" box="[1164,1273,799,823]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">P. bjostadi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens, the authors also collected males and females of 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D10FFBB0D47FB68FCB4FB038D27" authority="Kondratieff and Kirchner" authorityName="Kondratieff and Kirchner" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="puttmanni">
<emphasis id="B910EA81FFBB0D47FB68FCB4FC5B8D27" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">P. puttmanni</emphasis>
Kondratieff and Kirchner
</taxonomicName>
(
<specimenCount id="9D62FD1AFFBB0D47FAC3FC92FB368D27" box="[1230,1269,868,892]" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" type="male">6 ♂</specimenCount>
, 
<specimenCount id="9D62FD1AFFBB0D47FB0FFC92FAEB8D27" box="[1282,1320,868,892]" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" type="female">3 ♀</specimenCount>
) a new state record for NC (Kondratieff et al. 1995). Additionally, 
<emphasis id="B910EA81FFBB0D47FDC6FC5CFB958D9A" box="[971,1110,937,961]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">
<taxonomicName id="4C644D10FFBB0D47FDC6FC5CFB918D9A" baseAuthorityName="Newman" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[971,1106,937,961]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Acroneuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abnormis">A. abnormis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C644D10FFBB0D47FA6DFC5FFC488DBF" authority="Stark and Ray" authorityName="Stark and Ray" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" genus="Helopicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bogaloosa">
<emphasis id="B910EA81FFBB0D47FA6DFC5FFAF58D9A" box="[1120,1334,937,961]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">Helopicus bogaloosa</emphasis>
Stark and Ray
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="B910EA81FFBB0D47FD9AFC3AFB2E8DBF" box="[919,1261,972,996]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">
<taxonomicName id="4C644D10FFBB0D47FD9AFC3AFC3F8DBF" baseAuthorityName="Newman" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[919,1020,972,996]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ephyre">P. ephyre</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D10FFBB0D47FA05FC3AFBA98DBF" box="[1032,1130,972,996]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Perlinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zwicki">P. zwicki</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D10FFBB0D47FA7BFC3AFB2E8DBF" baseAuthorityName="Newman" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[1142,1261,972,996]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Neoperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="clymene">N. clymene</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D10FFBB0D47FAF1FC3AFC208A5D" authority="(Banks)" baseAuthorityName="Banks" baseAuthorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Paragnetina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fumosa">
<emphasis id="B910EA81FFBB0D47FAF1FC3AFCB08A5D" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">Paragnetina fumosa</emphasis>
(Banks)
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D10FFBB0D47FA4EFC19FB6D8A5D" box="[1091,1198,1006,1030]" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Alloperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lenati">
<emphasis id="B910EA81FFBB0D47FA4EFC19FB6D8A5D" box="[1091,1198,1006,1030]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">A. lenati</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were collected concurrently.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37E6518FFBB0D47FD25FBC2FAF18ACA" pageId="4" pageNumber="35" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BDB3693FFBB0D47FD25FBC2FAF18ACA" blockId="4.[808,1404,315,1169]" pageId="4" pageNumber="35">
